44–1179":"1144–1179","1180–1224":"1180–1224","1107–1166":"1107–1166","1120–Female":"1120–Overleden","before 1166":"vóór 1166","1198":"1198","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","1107":"1107","1149":"1149","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1166":"1166","1144":"1144","after 1179":"na 1179","Gonalston, Nottinghamshire, England":"Gonalston, Nottinghamshire, England","Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","South Wingfield, Derbyshire, England":"South Wingfield, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1150–1198":"1150–1198","1149–1179":"1149–1179","1152–Male":"1152–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1144–1179":"1144–1179","1180–1224":"1180–1224","1107–1166":"1107–1166","1120–Female":"1120–Deceased","before 1166":"before 1166","1198":"1198","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","1107":"1107","1149":"1149","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1166":"1166","1144":"1144","after 1179":"after 1179","Gonalston, Nottinghamshire, England":"Gonalston, Nottinghamshire, England","Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","South Wingfield, Derbyshire, England":"South Wingfield, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Heriz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Walloon: from a pet form of an ancient Germanic personal name with the element <i>heri</i> ‘army’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Heriz II was born in 1150, in South Wingfield, Derbyshire, England, his father, Ivo de Heriz I, was 43 and his mother, Emma de Bilborough, was 30. He married Agnes Alcher. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. In 1110, his occupation is listed as sheriff of nottingham. He died in 1198, in Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1150–1198":"1150–1198","1149–1179":"1149–1179","1152–Male":"1152–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1144–1179":"1144–1179","1180–1224":"1180–1224","1107–1166":"1107–1166","1120–Female":"1120–Surnud","before 1166":"enne 1166","1198":"1198","1120":"1120","1152":"1152","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","1107":"1107","1149":"1149","1224":"1224","1179":"1179","1166":"1166","1144":"1144","after 1179"